INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '7c12bf88-bf36-42b5-8368-7268e3d4ee0e',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Matplotlib + NumPy Vectorization — Plot 1M Points Without the Loop Tax$escape$,
  $escape$Matplotlib bindstightly to NumPy's memory layout. When you pass a Python list to plt.plot(), it internally converts to an ndarray — so you pay the conversion cost on every draw call. Pre-vectorizing your data eliminates this overhead and unlocks broadcasting for transforms.

C-contiguous arrays (row-major, NumPy's default) align with how Matplotlib's Agg backend reads vertex buffers. Passing a Fortran-ordered array forces a copy. Check with arr.flags['C_CONTIGUOUS'] before plotting large datasets.

Broadcasting shines when generating plot data. Instead of looping to compute y-values for multiple parameter curves, broadcast a column vector of x against a row vector of parameters — one expression, one allocation, one plot call via plt.plot(x, y_matrix). Matplotlib interprets each column as a separate series automatically.

For scatter plots with 100k+ points, vectorized color mapping via plt.cm.viridis(normalized_array) is ~50x faster than per-point color assignment. Always normalize with Normalize() before mapping.$escape$,
  $escape$import numpy as np
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

x = np.linspace(0, 4 * np.pi, 500)
freqs = np.array([[1, 2, 3, 5]])        # shape (1,4) — broadcast target
y = np.sin(x[:, np.newaxis] * freqs)     # shape (500,4) — vectorized, no loop

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(x, y)                            # each column drawn as a series
ax.set_title('Broadcasted sine curves')
ax.legend([f'{f}x' for f in freqs.flat])
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
