INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'ebe42e5b-ddc7-450e-b3b0-c0c9e79c3ab4',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$matplotlib + Polars — Plotting DataFrames Without Converting to Pandas$escape$,
  $escape$Polars DataFrames don't plug into matplotlib directly — plt.plot() expects NumPy arrays or Pandas Series. But converting is trivial, and the payoff is huge: Polars' lazy evaluation and expressions API let you filter, aggregate, and reshape millions of rows 5–10× faster than Pandas before you ever call plt.subplots().

The key pattern: build your entire data pipeline in Polars using lazy frames (.lazy() → .filter() → .group_by() → .agg() → .collect()), then extract columns as NumPy arrays via .to_numpy() for matplotlib. This avoids the Pandas intermediate entirely.

Polars expressions like pl.col('latency').mean().over('service') replace verbose Pandas groupby-transform chains in a single readable line. When your plotting script spends 80% of its time in data prep and 20% in rendering, Polars cuts total runtime dramatically.

Switch when: datasets exceed 1M rows, you chain 3+ transformations before plotting, or your notebook cells are bottlenecked on .groupby().agg() — not on plt.savefig().$escape$,
  $escape$import polars as pl
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

# Lazy pipeline — no work happens until .collect()
result = (
    pl.scan_csv("metrics.csv")
    .filter(pl.col("status") == 200)
    .group_by("endpoint")
    .agg(pl.col("latency_ms").mean().alias("avg_latency"))
    .sort("avg_latency", descending=True)
    .head(10)
    .collect()
)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.barh(result["endpoint"].to_numpy(), result["avg_latency"].to_numpy())
ax.set_xlabel("Avg Latency (ms)")
plt.tight_layout()
plt.savefig("top_endpoints.png", dpi=150)$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
