INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '469c93d9-5bfa-4ce7-b702-c23540d91b04',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Matplotlib heatmap() — Visualizing Correlation Matrices Without Seaborn$escape$,
  $escape$Most developers reach for seaborn's heatmap when visualizing correlations, but matplotlib's imshow() handles it natively with more control. Compute your correlation matrix with pandas, then render it using plt.imshow() with a diverging colormap like 'RdBu_r' centered at zero. The trick is pairing imshow() with plt.colorbar() and manually setting tick labels via ax.set_xticks() and ax.set_yticks() — this gives you full control over label rotation, font size, and grid alignment. For aggregation patterns like pivot tables, plot the pivoted DataFrame directly: pivot.plot(kind='bar', stacked=True, ax=ax) works, but imshow() on pivot.values produces cleaner heatmaps for dense tables. Use ax.text() to annotate individual cells with correlation coefficients — loop over the matrix with nested range() calls and format to two decimals. Set aspect='auto' when your matrix isn't square. Use vmin=-1, vmax=1 to lock the color scale across comparable charts.$escape$,
  $escape$import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np
import pandas as pd

df = pd.DataFrame(np.random.randn(100, 4), columns=['A', 'B', 'C', 'D'])
corr = df.corr()

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 5))
im = ax.imshow(corr, cmap='RdBu_r', vmin=-1, vmax=1, aspect='auto')
ax.set_xticks(range(len(corr))), ax.set_xticklabels(corr.columns, rotation=45)
ax.set_yticks(range(len(corr))), ax.set_yticklabels(corr.columns)
for i in range(len(corr)):
    for j in range(len(corr)):
        ax.text(j, i, f'{corr.iloc[i, j]:.2f}', ha='center', va='center', fontsize=9)
plt.colorbar(im, ax=ax, label='Correlation')
plt.tight_layout()
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
