INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  'f4187a1c-edd1-420e-ac44-57a78cc1a15d',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Matplotlib in Jupyter — Reproducible Plots with Parameterized Notebooks$escape$,
  $escape$Jupyter notebooks with matplotlib plots are notoriously hard to reproduce. Figures render differently across sessions when global state leaks between cells. Fix this by isolating each plot in its own figure context and pinning your style configuration at the notebook top.

Use `%matplotlib inline` with explicit `plt.figure()` calls instead of relying on implicit figure creation. For parameterized notebooks via Papermill, pass plot parameters (figsize, DPI, color palettes) as tagged cells so CI pipelines generate consistent visual outputs.

The key pattern: set `plt.rcParams` in a single setup cell, create every figure with `plt.subplots()` for explicit axes ownership, and call `fig.savefig()` with `bbox_inches='tight'` before `plt.show()`. This ensures your saved artifacts match what renders in-notebook.

For deterministic style across environments, use `plt.style.use()` with a checked-in `.mplstyle` file rather than inline `rcParams` scattered across cells. Papermill can then sweep parameters like date ranges while your plot styling stays version-controlled and reproducible.$escape$,
  $escape$import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import papermill as pm

# Tagged 'parameters' cell for Papermill injection
figsize = (10, 6)
dpi = 150
style_sheet = './house_style.mplstyle'

plt.style.use(style_sheet)
fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=figsize, dpi=dpi)
ax.plot([1, 2, 3], [1, 4, 9], linewidth=2)
ax.set_title('Parameterized Plot')
fig.savefig('output.png', bbox_inches='tight', dpi=dpi)
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
