INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '8d0441bf-c2e0-4ce0-a097-7a52aedf37f1',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Matplotlib — Validate Your Data Before Plotting with Pandera$escape$,
  $escape$Bad data silently produces misleading charts. A single NaN in your series causes matplotlib to skip points without warning, and mixed-type columns trigger cryptic casting errors deep inside `ax.plot()`. Catch these issues before they hit your figure.

Pandera lets you define a schema contract for your DataFrame, then validate it as a pre-plotting step. Define expected dtypes, value ranges, and nullability constraints. When validation fails, you get a clear error instead of a broken axis or invisible data gap.

The pattern is simple: validate → plot. Wrap your plotting functions so they enforce the schema on input data. This is especially critical for automated reporting pipelines where matplotlib renders charts from upstream ETL outputs — you won't be eyeballing every figure.

Key checks for plotting data: no NaN in x/y columns, numeric dtype enforcement, monotonically increasing x-values for time series, and bounded ranges that match your `ax.set_xlim()`/`ax.set_ylim()` calls. Fail fast, plot clean.$escape$,
  $escape$import pandera as pa
import pandas as pd
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt

schema = pa.DataFrameSchema({
    "timestamp": pa.Column(float, pa.Check.increasing()),
    "cpu_usage": pa.Column(float, pa.Check.in_range(0, 100), nullable=False),
})

df = pd.DataFrame({"timestamp": [1.0, 2.0, 3.0], "cpu_usage": [55.2, 72.1, 68.4]})
validated = schema.validate(df)

fig, ax = plt.subplots()
ax.plot(validated["timestamp"], validated["cpu_usage"])
ax.set_ylim(0, 100)
ax.set_ylabel("CPU %")
plt.show()$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
