INSERT INTO bytes.bytes (id, author_id, title, body, code_snippet, language, embedding, type, is_active, created_at, updated_at) VALUES (
  '90c94177-11a6-4331-bfb9-5a2189c2d147',
  '00000000-0000-0000-0000-000000000001',
  $escape$Matplotlib Reproducibility — Pinning Random Seeds for Consistent Plots$escape$,
  $escape$Matplotlib delegates randomness to NumPy, but your plots still drift between runs when you forget to seed before data generation AND before layout operations. Two pain points bite hardest: jittered scatter plots and stochastic color cycling via colormaps sampled with np.random.

Pin reproducibility at three layers. First, seed NumPy before any data generation. Second, freeze your matplotlib rcParams so font resolution and figure sizing stay deterministic across machines — export them with matplotlib.rc_params().keys(). Third, when converting notebooks to scripts, replace plt.show() with fig.savefig() using explicit dpi and bbox_inches='tight' to avoid renderer-dependent bounding box differences.

The silent killer: matplotlib's Agg backend and interactive backends rasterize text differently, producing pixel-level drift in saved PNGs. Lock the backend with matplotlib.use('Agg') before any import of pyplot. Combine this with a requirements pin on matplotlib's exact patch version, since minor releases occasionally change default tick formatting and spacing algorithms.$escape$,
  $escape$import matplotlib
matplotlib.use('Agg')  # lock backend before pyplot import
import matplotlib.pyplot as plt
import numpy as np

np.random.seed(42)

fig, ax = plt.subplots(figsize=(6, 4), dpi=150)
ax.scatter(np.random.randn(200), np.random.randn(200),
           c=np.random.rand(200), cmap='viridis', alpha=0.7)
ax.set_title('Reproducible Scatter')
fig.savefig('plot.png', bbox_inches='tight', dpi=150)
print(f'matplotlib=={matplotlib.__version__}')  # pin this in requirements.txt$escape$,
  $escape$python$escape$,
